(
  'Stump House Trail at Guillemot Cove',
  'A forest hike through a 184-acre Kitsap County nature reserve leading to "The Stump House" — a giant hollowed-out cedar stump with a roof built over it. Classic PNW enchanted-woods vibe, plus Hood Canal beach access at the bottom of the trail.',
  '19235 Stavis Bay Rd NW, Seabeck, WA 98380',
  'https://maps.google.com/?q=Guillemot+Cove+Nature+Reserve+Seabeck',
  47.6086, -122.9139,
  'activity',
  '{"All Ages", "3-5", "5+", "8+"}',
  'Wider PNW',
  'Free',
  '{"Outdoor / Nature", "Special / Treat", "Burn Energy"}',
  'This one feels like stepping into a fairytale. The Stump House — a massive hollowed cedar with a little roof on it — sparks instant imagination for kids (local legend says an outlaw named "Dirty Thompson" hid out here). The trail is an easy ~1-mile gravel descent through mossy forest, with Hood Canal beach access at the bottom if you want to make a longer day of it. It''s quieter than the big-name hikes, there''s almost always parking, and the whole place has that hidden-gem feel. Going as a ferry-and-drive day trip (Seattle → Bremerton → Seabeck) adds to the sense of adventure.',
  '{"The return trip is the catch — ~360 feet of elevation gain back up over one mile, and kids who sprinted down will drag on the way up. Plan for snacks and motivation", "No bathrooms anywhere on site — use the restroom before you turn onto Stavis Bay Rd", "No pets allowed in the reserve", "The meadow near the Stump House gets soggy Oct–May — wear waterproof boots or expect muddy shoes", "Not stroller-friendly — the trail is gravel with roots, switchbacks, and mud", "Parking is a small pullout with only a handful of spots — early or weekday arrivals are safest", "Trails fork in multiple places — grab the map at the trailhead kiosk so you don''t wander"}',
  'Pair it with the Seattle–Bremerton ferry for a full adventure day — makes the drive feel like part of the trip. Bring a picnic and head down to the beach after visiting the Stump House. Best in late spring through fall when the meadow is drier. Remind kids not to carve or damage the Stump House — it''s a community treasure.',
  '[{"name": "Seabeck Pizza", "description": "Reliable pizza spot in Seabeck, ~15 min from the trailhead"}, {"name": "Silver City Brewery (Silverdale)", "description": "Family-friendly brewpub on the way back, kid menu and burgers"}, {"name": "Monica''s Waterfront Bakery (Silverdale)", "description": "Great for coffee and pastries en route"}, {"name": "Pack a picnic", "description": "No food at the trailhead — a cooler in the car is the easiest play, and you can eat on the beach at the bottom"}]',
  null, null, null,
  'https://www.themandagies.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Guillemot-Cove-Natural-Reserve-Stump-House-Mandagies-scaled-2.jpg'
);
